# Commit often; keep PRs easy to review

## Commits

1. **Commit frequently** — after each logical slice (feature, fix, tests, docs), not only at the end of a large session.
2. **One concern per commit** when practical: app code, tests, and docs/rules can be separate commits.
3. Write **clear commit messages** (imperative mood, 1–2 sentences on *why*).
4. Only commit when the user asks, unless they have explicitly asked you to commit often as part of the task.
5. Run `npm run test:run` (and `npm run build` for substantial changes) before committing app code.

## Pull requests

When creating or updating PRs (required for new features per `sdlc-for-features.mdc`):

1. Keep PRs **focused** — one feature or theme per PR when possible.
2. Use a **Summary** (2–4 bullets: what changed and why) and a **Test plan** checklist.
3. Mention **breaking changes**, migrations (e.g. IndexedDB schema), and anything reviewers should try manually.
4. Avoid mixing unrelated refactors with feature work; split follow-up PRs if needed.
5. Link to `.prompts-history.md` when the PR is part of the AI-assisted demo workflow.

## Reviewer-friendly diffs

- Prefer small, named files over large single-file dumps.
- Update README when behavior visible to users changes.
- Include or update tests in the same PR as the behavior change.
